05Dt 15:1 "You must cancel your debts at the end of every seventh year. 
05Dt 15:2 This is the way to conduct remission£º every creditor must cancel the loan that his friend borrowed, and he must not pressure his friend or brother to repay it, because remission to the Lord will be proclaimed. 
05Dt 15:3 You may exact payment from a foreigner, but cancel whatever your brother owes you.
05Dt 15:4 "Moreover, there will be no poor person among you, for the Lord will surely bless you in the land that he is about to give you to possess. 
05Dt 15:5 Only be certain to obey the voice of the Lord your God. Carefully observe all of these commands that I'm commanding to you today. 
05Dt 15:6 For the Lord your God will bless you just as he promised. You are to lend to many nations but not borrow. Also, you will rule over many nations, but they will not rule over you."4
05Dt 15:7 "If there should be a poor man among your relatives in one of the cities of the land that the Lord your God is about to give you, don't be hard-hearted or tight-fisted toward your poor relative. 
05Dt 15:8 Instead, be sure to open your hand to him and lend him enough to lessen his need.
05Dt 15:9 "Be careful not to think this wicked thought to yourselves£º 'The seventh year, the year of remission, is drawing near,' and you show ill will toward your poor relative and not give to him. He may then call to the Lord on account of you, and you will be guilty of sin. 
05Dt 15:10 You must certainly give to him and not feel regret for doing so. Because of this, the Lord your God will bless all your works and everything you do. 
05Dt 15:11 Since poor people won't cease to exist in the land, therefore I'm commanding you£º Be sure to be generous to your poor and needy relatives in your land."
05Dt 15:12 "When a fellow Hebrew male or female slave is sold to you and serves you for six years, then in the seventh year you are to set them free. 
05Dt 15:13 But when you set them free, don't send them away empty-handed. 
05Dt 15:14 Provide for them liberally from your flock, threshing floor, and wine vat. As the Lord your God has blessed you, so give to them. 
05Dt 15:15 Don't ever forget that you were a slave in the land of Egypt, yet the Lord your God redeemed you. Therefore, I'm giving you these commands today.
05Dt 15:16 "Should that slave say to you, 'I won't leave you,' because he loves you and your household, and it was good for him to be with you, 
05Dt 15:17 then take an awl and pierce through his earlobe into the door. Then he will be your slave forever. You may do the same for your female slaves. 
05Dt 15:18 Don't view this as a hardship for yourself when you set him free, for he will have served you for six years - twice the time of a paid worker. Then the Lord will bless you in all that you do."
05Dt 15:19 "Set apart for the Lord your God every firstborn male among your herd and flock. You must not put the firstborn of your ox to work or shear the firstborn of your flock. 
05Dt 15:20 Then in the presence of the Lord your God, you and your household must eat them every year at the place the Lord will choose. 
05Dt 15:21 If it has a blemish - lameness, blindness, or any kind of defect - you must not sacrifice it to the Lord your God. 
05Dt 15:22 In your cities both the unclean and the clean together are to eat together, as the gazelle and the deer. 23Only you must not eat its blood. Pour it on the ground like water."
05Dt 16:1 "Observe the month of Abib, keeping the Passover to the Lord your God, because the Lord your God brought you out of Egypt during the night in the month of Abib. 
05Dt 16:2 Then sacrifice sheep and cattle for the Passover to the Lord your God at the place where the Lord your God will choose to establish his name. 
05Dt 16:3 You must not eat any yeast with it. Instead, for seven days eat bread without yeast - the bread of affliction - because you left the land of Egypt in haste. Remember the day you went out of the land of Egypt for the rest of your lives. 
05Dt 16:4 Yeast is not to be seen in any of your territories for seven days. The meat shall not remain from the evening of the first day until morning.2
05Dt 16:5 "You must not sacrifice the Passover in just any of your cities that the Lord your God is about to give you. 
05Dt 16:6 But at the place where your God will choose to establish his name, you are to sacrifice the Passover in the evening at dusk, at the time of day you left Egypt. 
05Dt 16:7 Boil and eat the Passover meal at the place that Lord your God will choose. In the morning you may go back to your tents. 
05Dt 16:8 Eat bread without yeast for six days. Then on the seventh day, hold an assembly to the Lord your God. Don't do any work."
05Dt 16:9 "Count off seven weeks from when the sickle is first put to standing grain. 
05Dt 16:10 Then observe the Feast of Weeks in the presence of the Lord your God by giving your tribute and the freewill offering of your hands in proportion to the manner in which the Lord your God blessed you.
05Dt 16:11 Rejoice in the presence of the Lord your God with your son, daughter, male and female slaves, the Levite who is in your city, the stranger, the orphan, and the widow among you, at the place where the Lord your God will choose to establish his name. 
05Dt 16:12 Remember that you were slaves in Egypt, so keep and observe these statutes."
05Dt 16:13 "Celebrate the Feast of Tabernacles for seven days after you harvest from your threshing floor and your wine press. 
05Dt 16:14 Rejoice in your festival - you, your son, your daughter, your male and female slaves, the Levites, foreigners, orphans, and widows who live in your cities. 
05Dt 16:15 For seven days you are to celebrate in the presence of the Lord your God at the place where the Lord will choose; for the Lord your God will bless you in all your harvest and in everything you do, and your joy will be complete.1614
05Dt 16:16 "Every male must appear in the presence of the Lord your God three times a year at the place where he will choose£º for the Feast of Unleavened Bread, the Feast of Seven Weeks, and the Feast of Tabernacles. He must not appear in the Lord's presence empty-handed, 
05Dt 16:17 but each one must appear with his own gift, proportional to the blessing that the Lord your God has given you."16
05Dt 16:18 "Appoint judges and civil servants according to your tribes in all your cities that the Lord your God is about to give you, so they may judge the people impartially. 
05Dt 16:19 You must not twist justice, show favoritism, or take bribes, because a bribe blinds the eyes of the wise and subverts the speech of the righteous. 
05Dt 16:20 You are to pursue justice - and only justice - so you may live and possess the land that the Lord your God is about to give you.
05Dt 16:21 "You are not to set up a sacred pole beside the altar of the Lord your God that you will build. 
05Dt 16:22 Furthermore, you are not to erect for yourselves a sacred stone pillar, because the Lord your God detests these things. 
05Dt 17:1 You are not to sacrifice to the Lord your God an ox and a sheep that has a defect or any flaw it, because that is detestable to the Lord your God."16
05Dt 17:2 "You may discover that a man or woman living in one of your cities that the Lord your God is about to give you has done evil in the eyes of the Lord your God by transgressing his covenant. 
05Dt 17:3 He may be following and serving other gods by bowing down to them - that is, to the sun, the moon, or to any of the heavenly host (something I did not command). 
05Dt 17:4 When it is reported to you or you hear of it, then investigate it thoroughly. When the truth has been established that this detestable thing has been done in Israel, 
05Dt 17:5 summon the man or the woman who did this evil thing to your city gates. Then stone the man or the woman to death. 
05Dt 17:6 Based on the testimony of two or three witnesses, they must surely die. But they are not to die based on the testimony of one person. 
