102Sm 24:12 "Go tell David, 'This is what the Lord says£º "I'm holding three choices out for you£º pick one of them for yourself, and I will do it to you."'"
102Sm 24:13 So Gad went to David and asked him, "Shall seven years of famine come to your land, or three months of reversals while you flee from your enemies as they pursue you, or three days of pestilence in your land?Decide right now what I am to answer to the one who sent me."
102Sm 24:14 So David replied to Gad, "This is a very difficult choice for me to make! Let me now please fall into the hand of the Lord, since his mercy is very great, but may I never fall into human hands!"
102Sm 24:15 That very morning, the Lord sent a pestilence to Israel until the conclusion of the time designated, and 70,000 men died from Dan to Beersheba. 
102Sm 24:16 As the angel was stretching out his hand to destroy Jerusalem, the Lord was grieved because of the calamity, so he told the angel who was afflicting the people, "Enough! Stay your hand!" So the angel of the Lord remained near the threshing floor that belonged to Araunah the Jebusite.
102Sm 24:17 When David saw the angel who had been attacking the people, he said to the Lord, "Look, I'm the one who has sinned! I did the evil. These are only sheep! What did they do?Please, let your hand fall on me and on my household!"
102Sm 24:18 That very day, Gad approached David and told him, "Go up and build an altar to the Lord on the threshing floor that belongs to Araunah the Jebusite." 
102Sm 24:19 So David went up, just as Gad had ordered, consistent with the Lord's command.18
102Sm 24:20 When Araunah looked down, he saw the king and his staff approaching him. Araunah went out, bowed down before the king with his face on the ground, 
102Sm 24:21 and asked him, "Why has your majesty the king come to his servant?"David replied, "To purchase your threshing floor and to build an altar to the Lord, so the pestilence can be averted from the people."
102Sm 24:22 Araunah responded to David, "May your majesty the king take it and offer whatever pleases him. Here are oxen for a burnt offering, along with the threshing sledges and yokes from the oxen for wood! 
102Sm 24:23 Your majesty, Araunah gives all of this to the king." Araunah also said to the king, "May the Lord your God be pleased with you!"
102Sm 24:24 "No!" the king replied to Araunah. "I will buy them from you at full price. I won't offer to the Lord my God burnt offerings that cost me nothing." So David bought the threshing floor and the oxen for 50 silver shekels, 
